Part 3: Visualization

Setup

library(ggplot2)  # if you installed tidyverse, you have it.  Otherwise install it first

Data

Were going to use the same penguins data from yesterday. If you didnt install it yesterday, do so now.

#install.packages("palmerpenguins")

If you have it installed, just load it:

library(palmerpenguins)

Were also going to use average yearly temperatures in New Hampshire, a data set built into R (nhtemp). But we need to put it in a data frame first to make it easier to use (its in a special time series object):

nh <- data.frame(temp=c(nhtemp), year=1912:1971)
nh

Base R Graphics

The core plotting function in R is plot(). It is used to make scatter plots and line plots.

plot(x = penguins$bill_depth_mm, 
     y = penguins$bill_length_mm)

As with other functions, naming the arguments x and y is optional - but plot expects x first then y:

plot(penguins$bill_depth_mm, penguins$bill_length_mm)

We can also use something called the formula syntax, which well talk about more tomorrow. With the formula syntax, we specify the data set, the we can use the variable names without quotes in the form: y ~ x

plot(bill_length_mm ~ bill_depth_mm, data=penguins)

Changes to the plot are made through other arguments (input options) to the plot() function, which are passed to the par() function. See the help for the par() function to get a list of options beyond the labels (which are part of plot() directly).

plot(bill_length_mm ~ bill_depth_mm, 
     data = penguins,
     main = "Penguin Bill Measurements",
     xlab = "Depth",
     ylab = "Height",
     pch = 17,  # which marker symbol to use
     col = "red",
     cex = 3,  # size
     ylim = c(30,65))

Colors can be specified with built in names (get a list with colors()) or hex values (web colors) or rgb() there are a few other options too.

Plot markers: https://bookdown.org/ndphillips/YaRrr/YaRrr_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-280-1.png

One option is the plot type, which is how we go from a scatter plot (default) to a line plot:

plot(temp ~ year, 
     data=nh,
     type='l')

There are other plotting functions built into R, but one I use frequently is hist():

hist(penguins$bill_depth_mm)

hist(penguins$bill_depth_mm, breaks=20)

ggplot2

I sometimes use base R plotting functions for very quick plots. And I have produced publication graphics with them before. But now most of the time I use ggplot2, which is particularly useful for exploring different groups in your data.

Open the ggplot2.Rmd tutorial file to continue. This is the same ggplot2 tutorial from the tidyverse workshop series.

Coming Up

Today youll practice plotting. I recommend picking one plotting system to focus on. If youre in a lab or work with colleagues who use base R graphics, then go with that. If not, Id start with ggplot2 from the beginning. It will likely take a little longer to get started as the basic syntax is a bit more complicated, but it will make it easier to make a wide range of plots after the initial learning period. There are links to both types of resources on the main page.

There are a few exercises, but the best approach for practicing today is to try to plot some of your own data or at least some data that youre interested in. Share the plots you make on the Canvas discussion boards. Theres a discussion topic for sharing visualizations even if theyre basic, show them off and celebrate your success!
